The magnetization curves of Co@CoO
x
@CG were measured at 300 K in a variable applied field (a). The hysteresis
loop of Co@CoO
x
@CG showed a coercive force
(H
c) of 480.97 Oe and remanent magnetization
(M
r) of 446.46 emu g–1 with a S
r = M
r/H
c value of 0.93. These parameters were
evidence for the ferromagnetism of Co@CoO
x
@CG (Figure S11). The ferromagnetism properties
with strong magnetic response make Co@CoO
x
@CG are easily isolated from water mixing system (Figure S12). The ZFC and FC magnetization curves of Co@CoO
x
@CG and Co@CoO
x
@N-CG were measured with an applied field of 500 Oe (c,d). The Co@CoO
x
@CG and Co@CoO
x
@N-CG showed ferromagnetic properties in 2–219.4
K and 2–215.3 K due to the existence of ferromagnetic Co. In
ZFC curves, Co@CoO
x
@CG and Co@CoO
x
@N-CG reached the maximum magnetization at
219.4 and 215.3 K, respectively. The weak temperature dependence of
magnetism ensures Co@CoO
x
@CG and Co@CoO
x
@N-CG be easily used in a wide temperature
range. The Co@CoO
x
@C and Co@CoO
x
@N–C showed similar performances (Figure S12).

